3-----Copy Constructor (C++ Only)

A copy constructor creates a new object as a copy of an existing object.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {

public:

    string name;

    Student(string n) {
        name = n;
    }

    Student(const Student &s) {
        name = s.name;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << name << endl;
    }
};

int main() {

    Student s1("Yash");

    Student s2 = s1;

    s2.display();

    return 0;
}

Output

Yash
Why?

Instead of writing values again, we copy another object's data.

Java does not have copy constructors built into the language. 
Objects are usually copied by creating a new object and copying fields manually or by using methods like clone().


5---------Constructor Overloading
What is it?

Having multiple constructors with different parameter lists in the same class.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {

public:

    Student() {
        cout << "Default" << endl;
    }

    Student(string name) {
        cout << name << endl;
    }

    Student(string name, int age) {
        cout << name << " " << age << endl;
    }
};

int main() {

    Student s1;

    Student s2("Yash");

    Student s3("Yash",22);

    return 0;
}

6----Destructor

A destructor is a special function used to destroy an object and release its resources.

C++
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {

public:

    Student() {
        cout << "Constructor Called" << endl;
    }

    ~Student() {
        cout << "Destructor Called" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {

    Student s1;

    return 0;
}
Output

Constructor Called
Destructor Called
Why?

When main() finishes, the object s1 goes out of scope, so the destructor runs automatically.


7-----Constructor vs Destructor
Constructor	                        Destructor
Creates/initializes object	        Cleans up object
Called when object is created     	Called when object is destroyed
Same name as class                 	Same name as class with ~ (C++)
Can have parameters	               Cannot have parameters
Can be overloaded               	Cannot be overloaded
Exists in Java and C++           	Exists only in C++
}
