1-----THIS Keyword
. Why do we use the this keyword?

We use the this keyword to refer to the current object of the class. It is mainly used to resolve the ambiguity between instance variables and local variables
(or constructor parameters) when they have the same name. It is also used for constructor chaining, calling current class methods, passing the 
current object, and returning the current object.


2-----Uses of this

There are 5 important uses.
****Refer to Current Object Variables ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Most common interview question.

class Student{

    String name;

    Student(String name){

        this.name = name;
    }
}
*****Use Case 2: Call Current Class Method ⭐⭐⭐⭐
Example
class Student {

    void study() {
        System.out.println("Studying...");
    }

    void display() {
        this.study();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Student s1 = new Student();

        s1.display();
    }
}
*****Use Case 3: Call Another Constructor (Constructor Chaining) ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
Example
class Student {

    Student() {
        this("Yash");
    }

    Student(String name) {
        System.out.println(name);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        new Student();
    }
}
*****Use Case 4: Pass Current Object as an Argument
******To return the current object.
Can we use this in a static method?

Answer:

No. A static method belongs to the class, not to an object, so there is no current object for this to refer to.

